Notes: Row ID uniquely identifies the drug prescription record itself, so mapping to the DrugPrescription's identifier property is semantically accurate. No 2-hop path provides a better semantic fit for a unique record identifier.

Patient ID relates directly to the patient entity linked via hasPatient and is best represented by the PatientIdentifier class, capturing patient identity semantics precisely. The 2-hop path through hasPatient to hasPatientIdentifier is better than a 1-hop direct property as no direct patient ID property exists on DrugPrescription.

ATC code identifies the drug prescribed, thus mapping through hasDrug to hasCode captures the drug coding accurately. A 2-hop path from Drug to Code is semantically more precise than assigning code directly at DrugPrescription level.

Diagnosis code is best mapped via hasIndicationToStart to the Diagnosis entity, then to its hasCode property, reflecting the clinical reasoning for the prescription. This 2-hop path is more semantically correct than mapping directly on DrugPrescription.

Creation date corresponds to the time the prescription was recorded, mapping directly to hasDateTime on DrugPrescription is appropriate. No better 2-hop path provides a more specific time property for creation date.

Times a day is frequency of drug administration, best modeled as a Quantity linked via hasFrequency with its numeric value via hasValue. The 2-hop path captures both the concept and its numeric value precisely.

Dosage represents the amount prescribed, best mapped via hasDrugQuantity to Quantity and its hasValue property. This 2-hop path semantically models dosage as a measurable quantity rather than free text.
